A country’s gross domestic product or GDP is a measure of the size and health of its economy. We can see in the list that the factor that most influence has on the GDP growth according with our model is the GDP annual growth of other years. This makes absolute sense since we want our model to predict that value for the next year.

The second factor that most importance has on the prediction of the GDP growth is the Foreign direct investment or FDI. The FDI is an investment made by a firm or individual in one country into business interests located in another country. Generally, FDI takes place when an investor establishes foreign business operations or acquires foreign business assets in a foreign company.

In the third position we have the Merchandise imports indicator. International merchandise import statistics measure the quantity, value, origin, etc of goods which are brought into a country permanently. They provide information about a countries trading role within the global economy. That is why it will have to be account to predict the GDP growth.

Apart from that, the selected as best indicators also provide information about population, environmental impact, GDP factors etc.

We will now train the data using the gradient boosting method to analise the impact those indicators have on the GDP growth prediction.

We know from the shap library that this kind of plots shows features each contributing to push the model output from the base value (the average model output over the training dataset we passed) to the model output. Features pushing the prediction higher are shown in red, those pushing the prediction lower are in blue. So in our case, in the fist row of our X_test the value is higher than the base value being the GDP per capita the only indicator lowering the value.

We will now make a summary plot of impact of each variable in each of the predictions done in the X_test. It can be seen that the factor that most influence has is the indicator corresponding to the GDP growth (annual %). We can see form the graph that it contributes positively in increasing the value of the GDP growth. Another factors that influence increasing could be the indicator CM.MKT.INDX.ZG corresponding to the S&P Global Equity Indices or the EN.ATM.CO2E.LF.KT indicator corresponding to the CO2 emissions from liquid fuel consumption.

On the contrary, it can also be seen that the indicators NY.ADJ.AEDU.GN.ZS and DT.DOD.DSTC.IR.ZS corresponding to the Adjusted savings: education expenditure and Short-term debt respectively contribute lowering the model output the model output.

In [22]:
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_test)

We will know analyse some of the features separately. We will start ploting the influence of the Country in the model.

In [23]:
shap.dependence_plot("COUNTRYENC", shap_values, X_test)

Vertical dispersion at a single value represents interaction effects with other features. In this case it is comparing the Country with the Services, etc., value added (annual % growth) for colouring. It can be seen that for most of the countries the Shap value remains almost the same. So maybe it was true that the country type didn't influence the model so much, and we shouldn't have enter it in the most influece indicator list.

In [26]:
shap.dependence_plot("NY.GDP.MKTP.KD.ZG", shap_values, X_test)

From the GDP growth indicator we can conclude that for negative values of the GDP growth the shap value decreases and for positive value of the GDP growth the Shap value increases. This makes sense because the greater the GDP growth the greater would be the predicted GDP value.

In [27]:
shap.dependence_plot("BX.KLT.DINV.WD.GD.ZS", shap_values, X_test)

A similar influence can be observed when analysing the Foreign direct investment.

In conclusion we can see that the values that have most influence in the model are not sorted in the same order that the list of the 50 best indicators we had obtained by training the model with all the indicators. This can be because there are lots of empty parameters in the SQL file so that the model doesn't train properly enough.
